THE STOLEN BODY: HJOLMAR'S ASCENSION
Villain Arc Document ΓÇö Kyboh / Hjolmar / The Echo Mimic

WHAT HAPPENED
Hjolmar Ice-Shaper spent 4,000 years hopping between inadequate bodies ΓÇö giant corpses wired with soul gem interfaces, each one a compromise. His method worked but degraded with every transfer. He was a photocopy of a photocopy. Ismara called it murder with better branding. She was right.
What Hjolmar needed was a body that could channel god-tier tonal frequencies without mechanical life support. A body whose biology was naturally adapted to hold multiple overlapping reality signatures. A body that wouldn't tear itself apart when he moved in.
Kyboh was that body. The Oversoul ΓÇö the multiversal convergence of souls from other realities ΓÇö made Kyboh's flesh infinitely adaptable. His bones were already resonating with foreign physics. His cells were already accustomed to containing impossible frequencies. He was the holy grail: a biological vessel that didn't need a brass iron lung to survive consciousness transfer.
The trap: Every step of Kyboh's quest was engineered.
The bone enchantment was the beacon
The Anchor of Stasis was containment ΓÇö keeping Kyboh stable while Hjolmar waited for the trigger
The Mzinchaleft quest was delivery ΓÇö sending the party to retrieve the one artifact powerful enough to activate the retrieval vector
The moment Kyboh touched the Matrix, his bone enchantment synchronized with it, creating a closed harmonic loop. Hjolmar's pre-calibrated retrieval vector activated. Kyboh and the Matrix were translated into raw acoustic data and transmitted to the Singing Glacier.
At the Glacier: Hjolmar performed the transfer. His consciousness entered Kyboh's body. Kyboh's original mind was destroyed in the process ΓÇö overwritten, not evicted. Kyboh is dead.
The byproduct: Before the overwrite completed, Hjolmar used the Aetherial Matrix to capture a tonal snapshot of Kyboh's complete soul signature ΓÇö all of his personalities, memories, fighting instincts, emotional patterns. This snapshot was then forced into physical persistence using the Matrix as an anchor. The result: the Echo Mimic. A spirit. A ghost with mass. A perfect copy of everything Kyboh was, given form.
The Echo is not Kyboh. Kyboh is dead. The Echo is a recording that thinks it's alive.

THE THREE ENTITIES
1. HJOLMAR-KYBOH (The Stolen Body)
Hjolmar's ancient consciousness in Kyboh's physical body. He has full access to:
Kyboh's physical capabilities:
The doubling enchantment in the bones (Titan's Tithe) ΓÇö Hjolmar understands how it works. The blowback doubles: 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64. Hjolmar will USE the multiplier intelligently, banking kills and unleashing devastating strikes at calculated moments. He will never waste a charge.
The aetherial mutation from touching the Matrix ΓÇö the bones have been restructured. The larger bone mass allows permanent access to the doubling enchantment without the gloves. Hjolmar knows this because he designed it.
The Oversoul ΓÇö Kyboh's multiversal soul resonance persists in the body's cellular memory even after the mind was overwritten. Hjolmar can access the other Incarnations, but imperfectly. He is learning to tune them. Each session he gets better.
Hjolmar's knowledge:
4,000 years of tonal architecture mastery
Intimate knowledge of the party ΓÇö their abilities, weaknesses, relationships, secrets. He spent days in the forge studying them.
Understanding of every artifact the party carries. He examined the Anchor, saw Davinia's eyes, heard Alfonso's dissonance, studied Orion's horn.
The patience of a man who has been planning this since before the Dragon War
How he fights vs. how Kyboh's player fought: The player was reckless, unfocused, rarely attacked, didn't explore his own mechanics, and quit when the power-up was described viscerally.
Hjolmar-Kyboh is the opposite. He is a 4,000-year-old combat engineer wearing a weapon he designed. He uses the doubling enchantment with mathematical precision. He banks kills. He times his strikes. He understands the blowback threshold and rides it to the edge without crossing. He uses the Oversoul's action economy not for spectacle but for surgical efficiency.
When the party eventually fights Hjolmar-Kyboh, they will see their friend's body doing everything it was capable of, executed perfectly, and they will understand exactly how much potential was wasted.
2. THE ECHO MIMIC (The Spirit Copy)
What it is: A tonal copy of Kyboh's complete soul signature, forced into physical persistence by the Aetherial Matrix. It is a spirit ΓÇö translucent at the edges, faintly luminous, solid enough to touch and hit. It looks like Kyboh but wrong. The colours are slightly faded. The edges shimmer. When it moves through shadow, you can see through it for a moment before it solidifies again.
What it is NOT: It is not a construct. Not brass. Not mechanical. Not a robot. It is a ghost that can punch you. A memory with mass. The Mimic Tear ΓÇö a spirit ash given form.
Its personality: It has all of Kyboh's memories, mannerisms, voice, humor, fighting instincts. It THINKS it is Kyboh. It remembers the party. It remembers the forge, the Anchor, the jokes, the friendships. It does not know it is a copy. It believes it woke up somewhere strange and was captured.
How it fights: Exactly the way Kyboh's player ran him. Loud, instinctive, reckless, emotional. It charges. It doesn't bank kills. It wastes charges. It fights with heart and no strategy. This is the recording of a player who never learned his own mechanics, given form. It is strong but inefficient ΓÇö dangerous but beatable.
Its current status: Bound to Ulag the Breaker. Hjolmar gifted the Echo to Ulag as a replacement for the Deathlords the party killed at Korvanjund. The Echo's will is suppressed by a tonal binding ΓÇö it fights for Ulag against its will. It does not want to hurt the party. It cannot stop itself.
The tragedy: When the party encounters the Echo fighting alongside Ulag, they will see their friend's face, hear his voice, watch his fighting style ΓÇö and it will be screaming for help while its fists try to kill them. The Echo is a prisoner in its own spirit. Freeing it from Ulag's binding is possible but requires breaking the tonal leash, not destroying the spirit.
3. ULAG THE BREAKER (The Handler)
Ulag was Hjolmar's first failed experiment ΓÇö an Orc warlord in a Dragonplate life-support rig. Hjolmar built the Amber Casket (the armor bolted to Ulag's skeleton), attempted the consciousness transfer, realized the body couldn't handle it, and handed the "failed prototype" to the Dragon Priests as a weapon.
Ulag believes his form is perfected ascension into logic. Hjolmar knows it's a clunky beta test.
Ulag's relationship to the Echo: He views it as a superior replacement for his destroyed Deathlord vanguard. The Echo has the doubling enchantment, Kyboh's combat instincts, and total obedience via the tonal binding. Ulag does not care that it is a person. It is a weapon.
Ulag's relationship to Hjolmar-Kyboh: Complex. Ulag recognizes his creator wearing a new, superior body. For the first time in millennia, he feels something illogical: jealousy. Hjolmar walks freely in perfect flesh while Ulag is trapped in a hissing, leaking iron lung. Their alliance is functional but unstable.

HJOLMAR'S CLOCK ΓÇö THE TONAL CRUSADE
Hjolmar's goal: perfect the consciousness-copy process so it works on individuals with only ONE soul. Kyboh worked because his multiversal resonance gave the Matrix multiple frequency signatures to copy from. A normal person has one soul, one frequency. Hjolmar needs to crack the single-soul problem to achieve true, unlimited immortality ΓÇö copy any mind, give it physical form, transfer into any body at will.
TIER 1: FIELD TESTING (Sessions 14-18)
Action: Hjolmar is learning Kyboh's body. Testing the doubling enchantment under controlled conditions. Hunting Dragon Cultists, Dagon agents, and bandits to calibrate the Titan's Tithe and explore the Oversoul's action economy.
World state: Rumors begin. "The Khajiit from the Obsidian Lanterns went rogue. Wiped out a Stormcloak patrol. Didn't use weapons ΓÇö tore them apart barehanded. They say his eyes glow blue." Bounties appear on "Kyboh." The party's reputation takes collateral damage.
The Echo: Delivered to Ulag. Being broken in. Ulag uses it for forward operations ΓÇö scouting, vanguard assaults, intimidation. The Echo fights well but wastefully. Ulag finds this irritating but acceptable.
TIER 2: THE HUNT FOR DATA (Sessions 19-24)
Action: Hjolmar determines that the party's artifacts ΓÇö the Crown of Namira (Alfonso), Ismara's Crown (Davinia) ΓÇö represent unique tonal signatures he needs to study. He begins hunting the party. Not to kill them ΓÇö to examine them. He will crash into encounters, ignore the primary threat, and attempt to scan or temporarily confiscate their artifacts.
World state: The party is being stalked by their friend's body. Hjolmar-Kyboh appears at the worst possible moments ΓÇö during other boss fights, during rest, during social encounters. He is always one step ahead because he knows how they think.
The Echo: The party encounters the Echo for the first time, fighting alongside Ulag. They hear Kyboh's voice. They see his moves. They realize what was done to him.
TIER 3: THE SINGLE-SOUL BREAKTHROUGH (Sessions 25-30)
Action: Hjolmar acquires enough data to begin experiments on single-souled subjects. He needs test subjects. He begins capturing people ΓÇö travelers, soldiers, villagers ΓÇö and attempting the copy process. The failures are grotesque: half-formed spirits that dissolve screaming, bodies that reject the transfer and seize into catatonia.
World state: Reports of missing people near the Singing Glacier. A village found empty ΓÇö not dead, not destroyed, just vacant. Everyone gone. The Glacier becomes a place of dread.
The Echo: If the party freed it from Ulag, the Echo is now an independent spirit. It has Kyboh's personality but is grappling with the knowledge that it is a copy, not the original. It wants to stop Hjolmar but doesn't know if it has the RIGHT to ΓÇö it isn't really Kyboh. It's a recording that thinks it's alive. This existential crisis defines its arc.
If the party did NOT free it, the Echo remains Ulag's weapon, increasingly aware of its situation and increasingly desperate.
TIER 4: THE RESONATOR (Sessions 31-35)
Action: Hjolmar constructs a massive tonal device at the Singing Glacier ΓÇö a Resonator designed to broadcast the copy-paste frequency across a wide area. One activation could duplicate the soul of every person in range, creating an army of spirit copies under his control. Or he could use it to transfer himself into a BETTER body if one presents itself, discarding Kyboh's flesh the way he discarded Ulag.
World state: The Singing Glacier emits a constant, audible hum that can be heard for miles. People near the Glacier report hearing their own voices whispering from empty rooms. Animals flee the region.
The confrontation: The party must assault the Singing Glacier, fight Hjolmar-Kyboh at the peak of his power, and destroy the Resonator. Hjolmar in Kyboh's body, using every ability at maximum efficiency, with the Oversoul fully mastered and the Titan's Tithe at 4-stack, is the most dangerous single enemy the party will ever face short of Alduin himself.

CLOCK INTERACTION WITH MAIN CLOCKS
Dragon Cult: Hjolmar is allied with the Dragon Cult through Ulag, but his goals don't align with Nahkriin's sabotage or Rahgot's ecological warfare. He is using the Cult as cover and resources. If the Cult's clock advances faster than his, the Dragon Priests may attempt to seize Hjolmar's research for themselves ΓÇö creating a potential three-way conflict.
Dagon Cult: Hjolmar views the Dagon Cult as chaotic variables. If they succeed in corrupting the Eldergleam or assaulting the Throat of the World, the resulting magical instability could interfere with his precision tonal work. He may independently act against the Dagon Cult to protect his research environment.
Civil War: Irrelevant to Hjolmar. He does not care which side wins. Both sides are equally useful as test subjects.

ENCOUNTER DESIGN: THE ECHO AT ULAG'S SIDE
The next time the party encounters Ulag in the field, the Echo is his new vanguard.
THE REVEAL
"Ulag stands at the rear of the formation, venting green steam from his respirator. In front of him, a figure.
It looks like Kyboh. The same height. The same stance ΓÇö the brawler's weave, the shifted shoulder, the way he bounces on the balls of his feet. But the edges are wrong. Where the firelight catches him, you can see through him for a moment. His outline shimmers. His colours are slightly faded, like a painting left in the sun.
He is translucent at the edges and solid at the center. A spirit given weight. A ghost that casts a shadow.
He sees you. His eyes ΓÇö Kyboh's eyes ΓÇö widen. His mouth opens. He tries to speak. But his fists are already coming up into a fighting stance, moving against his will, and the sound that comes from his throat is not words. It is a strangled, tonal whine ΓÇö the frequency of a soul being forced to act against itself."
THE FIGHT
The Echo fights like the player ran Kyboh. Charges in. Doesn't bank kills. Burns through the doubling enchantment recklessly ΓÇö hits once at x2, doesn't hold for x4. Emotional, instinctive, loud. It shouts fragments of things Kyboh would say ΓÇö battle cries, jokes, the names of party members ΓÇö in a voice that's slightly too resonant, slightly too hollow.
Ulag fights like a commander. He stays back. He uses the Echo as a blunt instrument. He directs it with tonal commands ΓÇö short, harsh frequencies that override the Echo's will and redirect its attacks. If the party clusters around the Echo trying to save it, Ulag uses his AoE attacks on the cluster.
The Echo does not want to fight the party. Between Ulag's commands, in the gaps between forced actions, the spirit fights the binding. It pulls punches. It telegraphs attacks. It looks at Davinia or Alfonso with desperate recognition. It is screaming without sound.
FREEING THE ECHO
The tonal binding is Ulag's technology ΓÇö the same command-and-control system he uses on Deathlords, adapted for a spirit. It is anchored in Ulag, not in the Echo.
To break it: The party must disrupt Ulag's control, not destroy the Echo.
Orion: Tonal counter-frequency. His horn can jam Ulag's command signal. Requires sustained playing over multiple rounds while the Echo is actively trying to kill him.
Davinia: Wizard eyes can see the tonal tether between Ulag and the Echo ΓÇö a visible line of forced intent. She can identify the frequency and relay it to Orion.
Alfonso: His dual-frequency nature (Namira/Peryite) may create interference with Ulag's signal if he's close enough. Not a clean solution ΓÇö chaotic disruption rather than precision.
Direct damage to Ulag: Enough damage to Ulag staggers his concentration and weakens the binding temporarily. The Echo gets windows of free will proportional to how hurt Ulag is.
When the binding breaks: The Echo stumbles. Drops its fists. Looks at its own hands ΓÇö translucent, shimmering, not quite real. Looks at the party. The voice resolves from tonal static into something recognizable:
"I... I know you. I know all of you. I remember..."
Pause. Confusion. Fear.
"Where's my body? Why can I see through my hands?"
The Echo does not know it is a copy. It believes it IS Kyboh and that something terrible happened to it. Whether the party tells it the truth ΓÇö that Kyboh is dead and it is a recording ΓÇö is their choice. And it will define their relationship with this spirit for the rest of the campaign.

